We question Doug Smart, MD of KFC SA.What&rsquo;s the most interesting thing about you that people don&rsquo;t know?In 1988, I was in the winning eight-man team at the SA Skydiving Nationals.How do you handle stress?I remind myself that what&rsquo;s big for me is nothing when observed from an eternal perspective. I create headroom; I don&rsquo;t overfill the diary. I share what&rsquo;s going on in my life with my wife and I get outside and ride.What is your biggest indulgence?My mountain bikes. Yes, I have more than one.What was your first job?Singer/musician at Turn &rsquo;n Tender in Edenvale.Which phrase or word do you most overuse?"That&rsquo;s right."What&rsquo;s your one top tip for doing a deal?Know what you want before going in, listen intently, seek to understand the other party&rsquo;s point of view and always do the right thing.Where were you when Nelson Mandela was released from prison?I was living in Melbourne, Australia at the time, watching attentively on TV.What&rsquo;s the worst airport you&rsquo;ve been in?Lagos, Nigeria.Who is your favourite hero of fiction?This will date me: Jack Ryan.Tell us about a hidden gem in SA that not many people know about.The Spruit in Jo&rsquo;burg. A remarkable, flowing urban mountain bike trail running behind houses and under roads along the Braamfontein Spruit, from Paulshof to Emmarentia and beyond to Alberts Farm.What are you reading at the moment?Trevor Noah&rsquo;s Born a Crime &mdash; poignant, funny and quintessentially South African.When and where are or were you happiest?I lived in Fiji from 2000 to 2003; I was running a business there for an Australian company. My sons were 8, 9, and 10 years old, and my family made many lifelong friends and had countless amazing adventures together.What is the one investment you wish you had made, or made earlier?I wish I had bought Apple stock for US$2 in 2004. The stock price is $136 today.Is there such a thing as "enough money", and if so, how much is it?Yes there is. I don&rsquo;t have a number in mind, but it is the amount that allows one to provide for one&rsquo;s family and live life wholeheartedly, but without extravagance. I have learnt that the happiest people are not those who have the most, but those who need the least.